{"metadata":{"id":"CUBA_62","title":"DEFCON 2: The 13 Days","description":"October 1962. You are inside the ExComm Situation Room. Soviet nuclear missiles have been detected 90 miles from Florida. The window for diplomacy is closing, and the military is demanding an airstrike. Your decisions will determine if the Cold War turns hot.","author":"Classroom Sim Architect","version":"60.1"},"theme":{"accent":"#d2b48c","fontH":"Courier New, monospace","fontP":"Georgia, serif","splashHeroURL":"https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/splash-kennedy-1.jpg"},"intelligenceGlossary":[{"term":"ExComm","definition":"The Executive Committee of the National Security Council. The ad-hoc group of advisors (inc. RFK, McNamara, Bundy) assembled by JFK to handle the crisis."},{"term":"DEFCON","definition":"Defense Readiness Condition. An alert state used by the US Armed Forces. DEFCON 2 is 'Next step to nuclear war'—the highest level ever reached."},{"term":"Quarantine","definition":"A naval blockade. The term was carefully chosen because a 'blockade' is technically an act of war under international law, whereas a 'quarantine' implies defensive containment."},{"term":"MRBM / IRBM","definition":"Medium-Range (1,000 miles) and Intermediate-Range (2,000+ miles) Ballistic Missiles. The SS-4 and SS-5s found in Cuba."},{"term":"OPLAN 312","definition":"The US Military's operational plan for a massive airstrike against Cuba, followed by OPLAN 316 (full invasion)."},{"term":"Backchannel","definition":"Unofficial, secret communication lines (e.g., via journalists or embassies) used to negotiate without public posturing."},{"term":"SAM","definition":"Surface-to-Air Missile. Soviet defensive weapons (like the SA-2) capable of shooting down high-altitude spy planes."}],"reflections":{"pre":[],"pre_narrative":"OCTOBER 16, 1962. The world stands on the razor's edge. For decades, the Cold War has been a game of shadows—spies, proxies, and threats. But today, the shadow has become a solid object.\n\nSurveillance flights have confirmed the impossible: The Soviet Union is secretly constructing offensive nuclear missile sites in Cuba, just 90 miles from American soil. If these missiles become operational, they will be able to strike Washington D.C. in under 15 minutes, bypassing all early warning systems.\n\nInside the White House, the Executive Committee (ExComm) has convened. The room is thick with smoke and fear. The Joint Chiefs of Staff are demanding an immediate airstrike to destroy the sites before they are active. Diplomatic advisors warn that striking Cuba could trigger a Soviet counter-strike on Berlin or a full nuclear exchange.\n\nYou are an intelligence analyst embedded within the Situation Room. Your screen displays the raw feed: grain U-2 photos, intercepted telex cables, and the shifting positions of the Soviet fleet. The President is looking to you for a cool-headed analysis of the data. Your job is not to fight, but to think.","post":["The 'Fog of War' describes the uncertainty in situational awareness. In Exhibit C (The Quarantine), how did imperfect information about the Soviet submarines impact your willingness to authorize force?","General LeMay argued that strength and aggression were the only languages the Soviets understood, while RFK argued for a 'moral' solution to avoid a surprise attack. Which philosophy do you believe was truly more dangerous in this context?","In the final negotiation (The Turkey Trade), the US publicly refused to trade missiles but privately agreed to it. Was this deception necessary to save face, or did it betray democratic transparency?","Review your decision in Exhibit E (The Shootdown). When Major Anderson was killed, the Standing Orders demanded retaliation. If you chose to hold fire, why did you disobey protocol? If you fired, what was the result?"],"post_narrative":"The Cuban Missile Crisis ended on October 28, 1962, when Khrushchev agreed to dismantle the missiles in exchange for a US pledge not to invade Cuba and a secret agreement to remove Jupiter missiles from Turkey. The world had come within hours of nuclear annihilation. Kennedy's restraint, combined with backchannel diplomacy, prevented World War III. But the crisis revealed how fragile peace truly was—and how easily miscalculation, pride, or a single rogue commander could destroy civilization. Your decisions in this simulation reflect the same pressures faced by the ExComm: incomplete information, impossible choices, and the weight of history."},"epilogue":{
